  "prompt": "How much tax do a non resident earning 60000$/annum have to pay in USA?",
  "response": "In the United States, non-resident aliens are subject to U.S. tax on their U.S.-source income. The specific amount of tax that a non-resident earning $60,000 per year would need to pay can depend on several factors, including:\n\n1. **Source of Income**: If the income is from U.S. sources and is considered effectively connected income (ECI) with a trade or business in the U.S., it is typically taxed at the same rates that apply to U.S. citizens and residents.\n\n2. **Tax Treaties**: The U.S. has tax treaties with many countries that may provide for lower tax rates or exemptions on certain types of income. The terms of these treaties vary, so it\u2019s important to consult the specific treaty for the country of residence.\n\n3. **Filing Status**: Non-resident aliens typically file Form 1040-NR. They do not get the same standard deductions as residents, but they can deduct certain expenses that are directly related to their income.\n\nAssuming the non-resident's income is subject to U.S. tax without any deductions or treaty benefits, the tax rate will be based on the 2023 IRS tax brackets for non-resident aliens. For a single filer, the tax brackets generally look as follows:\n\n- 10% on income up to $11,000\n- 12% on income over $11,000 to $44,725\n- 22% on income over $44,725 to $95,375\n\nUsing these brackets, the calculation for a single non-resident earning $60,000 would be:\n\n1. First $11,000: 10% of $11,000 = $1,100\n2. Next $33,725 ($44,725 - $11,000): 12% of $33,725 = $4,047\n3. Remaining $15,275 ($60,000 - $44,725): 22% of $15,275 = $3,360.50\n\nAdding these amounts:\n\n- $1,100 (10% portion) \n- $4,047 (12% portion) \n- $3,360.50 (22% portion)\n\nTotal Tax = $1,100 + $4,047 + $3,360.50 = **$8,507.50**\n\nKeep in mind that this is a simplified calculation and other factors can affect the final tax owed, including any applicable tax credits, allowable deductions, or specific circumstances related to the individual's tax situation. It is highly recommended to consult with a tax professional or utilize tax preparation services for accurate and personalized advice.",
